Mr. Strong announced in December that he was looking for a buyer for his stake in Strong Capital, and Wells Fargo, the big San Francisco-based bank, is the leading candidate to acquire the company, people briefed on the talks have said. Wells was waiting for the regulators' investigation to be resolved before it would consider an agreement to buy the company, these people said.A spokesman for the bank declined to comment yesterday.A sale would come after Mr. Strong hurt the business he worked so long to develop. Assets at the company declined to $33.8 billion under management at the end of April from $43 billion at the end of September, weeks before Mr. Strong's trading became public.Mr. Strong will probably get much less for his interest in the company than he sought when he put it up for sale. Mr. Strong had hoped for close to $1 billion, people briefed on the sale negotiations said; now he is likely to get half that amount.One fund industry analyst said he was surprised that Mr. Spitzer had not pursued a criminal case against Mr. Strong.''Mr. Spitzer had been holding up Strong as a poster child for going to jail,'' said Roy Weitz, who runs a Web site called FundAlarm.com. ''There's some suggestion that the steam is running out of this investigation,'' with regulators eager to settle and move on, he said.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Spitzer acknowledged that some critics would say that he should have brought charges against Mr. Strong. But he said that he did not bring a criminal case against Mr. Strong because market timing was not clearly illegal.In the fund investigation to date, Mr. Spitzer said, ''the criminal cases we've made all relate to late trading,'' he said, which refers to trades made after the market has closed but at an earlier price. Such trading is clearly illegal, he said, but the legality of market timing is more ambiguous.Mr. Spitzer said he had insisted on a statement of contrition by Mr. Strong, rather than a refusal to admit or deny charges, a feature of prior settlements. That statement could figure in future securities litigation against Mr. Strong, Mr. Weitz said.Mr. Strong's lawyer, Stanley S. Arkin, made clear that Mr. Strong was aware of the impact of his behavior on the company he founded.''In reaching this civil settlement, Dick had very much in mind that he wished to preserve the jobs and the futures of the many loyal and talented people at Strong Capital, and at the same time enable the funds to continue for the future benefit of all of their shareholders,'' Mr. Arkin said. Mr. Strong was not available for comment, Mr. Arkin said.Kenneth J. Wessels, who was named chairman and chief executive of Strong last December, said yesterday, ''These settlement agreements allow us to move forward and concentrate all of our energies on meeting the needs of our clients.''Two other employees of the company were named in yesterday's settlement. Thomas A. Hooker Jr., who had been director of compliance at Strong Capital, and Anthony J. D'Amato, an executive vice president, have also agreed to a ban from the industry.Mr. D'Amato will pay $750,000 in penalties and disgorgement; Mr. Hooker will pay a $50,000 civil penalty.A spokeswoman for Strong Capital said the two men were no longer at the company.''The case reflects the increased attention compliance officers are receiving in a new era of enforcement of the securities laws,'' said Richard Morvillo, a lawyer for Mr. Hooker.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

A lawyer for Mr. D'Amato did not return calls. Continue reading the main story






